^B@2hondo717: Ok, the first thing on this hand is the declarer technique of playing out all your winners, when you only have one loser remaining, and hope the opponents make a discarding  error. But the more important issue is how to bid once you transfer. So let me review it. |
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


NT|
^B@2hondo717: Once you initiate a transfer, the 1N bidder knows you have at least 5 cards in the transfer suit. So if the 1N bidder has 3 card support, he will know to return to the transfer suit rather than allow the hand to be played in NT. Therefore, once you transfer, your possible actions are as follows: 
With 0-7 points you pass.|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT|
^B@2hondo717: With 8 or 9 points, you bid 2N. This tells pard you have a 5 card suit, and an invitational hand.
With 15 or 16, opener does not want to accept the invitation. In which case, the 1N bidder passes with 2 card support, and bids 3@H with 3 card support. On the other hand with a good 16 or 17, opener accepts the invitation and bids 3N with 2 card support, and 4 hearts with 3 card support.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT|
^B@2hondo717: With a game forcing hand and a 5 card suit, the transfer bidder bids 3N, as aggie did on this hand. The opener  either pass with 2 card support, as I did, or bid 4@H with 3 card support. The key to remember is that when the responder transfers, they are guaranteeing a 5 card suit. the 1N bidder knows this, and can bid accordingly, playing in the transfer suit with 3 card support, and in NT with 2 card support. |
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT|
^B@2hondo717: With a six card suit, it is a bit different, 
1. With 0-7, responder still transfers and passes. 
2. With 8 or 9 and a six card suit, responder bids 3 of the suit. That shows exactly 8 or 9 and a six card suit. Typically, the NT bidder will either pass if he does not accept the invitation, usually with 15 or a bad 16 and 2 card support. The 1N bidder will accept the invitation with 16 or more (and sometimes even with 15 and 3 card support.)|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT|
^B@2hondo717: With 5 hearts and 5 spades it is a bit different. With 5/5:
1) If responder has a game forcing hand, bid 2@H (transfer to spades) and then jump to 4@H (e.g 1N-2@H-2@S-4@H)
2) If responder has an invitational hand, bid 2@H (transfer to spades) and then bid 3@H (this is by agreement, since some might play this is game forcing with 5 spades and 4 hearts)
3) With a less than invitational hand, transfer to your best suit. |
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT|
^B@2hondo717: With 5/4:
1) With game forcing hand, if you do not play smolen, bid Stayman and then jump to 3 of your 5 card suit  (e.g. 1N-2@C-2@D-3@H)  If you play smolen, then with, say, 5 hearts and 4 spades, the auction is 1N-2@C-2@D-3@S; with smolen, this auctions shows 5 hearts and 4 spades and a game-going hand, but allows the NT bidder to be declarer in whatever is the best contract.
2) With an invitational hand, bid Stayman and bid your 5 card suit over the 2@D response (e.g. 1N-2@C-2@D-2@S).
3) With a less than invitational hand, transfer to your 5 card suit. Okay, let us move to the next board.

